The Resurgence of a Great Leader
LONDON —— It has been two centuries since the Battle of Waterloo, where Napoleon's catastrophic defeat severely damaged France's self-respect to such an extent that General de Gaulle omitted any mention of this battle when writing about French military history.
Nevertheless, if you acknowledge "greatness" as a personal quality, both Napoleon and de Gaulle could be considered among the greatest leaders in history.
Marx and Tolstoy would say that there is no such thing as a "great leader".
In Marx's view, the class struggle in France created the environment in which a "grotesque mediocrity" like Napoleon could become a hero.
In Tolstoy's view, Napoleon was not an especially outstanding general, and his victories should be credited to the courage and dedication of the French soldiers who fought in the Battle of Borodino.
Whether or not Napoleon was great, we need to determine whether "greatness" can be used to describe any leader.
If the answer is affirmative, then who can be described as great?
Political philosopher Isaiah Berlin believed that a great leader must meet two particularly important criteria.
First, is the leader able to recognize the trends of history?
Otto von Bismarck did, as did his German compatriot Konrad Adenauer; borrowing Bismarck's memorable phrase, both heard "the rustling of the cloak of God."
Secondly, did the leader make important decisions?
Of course, if a leader was forced to make decisions, he or she could neither be blamed for them nor take credit for them.
Therefore, the key is whether the leader had the opportunity to weigh the pros and cons and make the correct decisions on behalf of the nation.
De Gaulle therefore rightly deserves a place on any list of great leaders.
Almost single-handedly, he led France out of the post-World War II decline zone.
After regaining power in 1958, he once again saved his country, suppressed two failed coups, ended the Algerian War, and drafted the Constitution of the Fifth Republic.
Similar to British Prime Minister Winston Churchill, de Gaulle gave the French a new worldview and established their position in the global order after the war.
In fact, the ultimate impact of de Gaulle and Churchill in establishing their nations' worldviews was somewhat excessive.
Their successors viewed the world —— as well as their own country's role —— in ways that constrained rational discussion and distorted decision-making for many years afterwards.
The result was that the leaders of the two countries afterwards were never able to achieve accomplishments that could rival those of the two great leaders.
But there is still one British prime minister who can be compared to them: she is Margaret Thatcher, a very controversial figure, equally liked and disliked by people.
Even her resignation 25 years ago stemmed from resistance within her own cabinet and party.
However, it is not necessary to be loved by everyone in order to be a great leader.
In fact, even Thatcher's critics could not deny her influence.
Aside from being the first female prime minister of Britain and nearly the earliest female prime minister in other countries as well, Thatcher helped reverse Britain's economic decline.
Moreover, her attack on the overly powerful unions enhanced the country's manageability at a time when it seemed to be sliding into turmoil and chaos.
Given this, she undoubtedly has the right to be considered a candidate for "great leader."
Similarly, although far from flawless, Deng Xiaoping of China is also qualified to be considered a great leader.
Aside from assisting Mao in wrongdoing, Deng played a decisive role in ordering the 1989 Tiananmen Square massacre.
But Deng simultaneously revitalized the market, leading China onto an unprecedented path of development and prosperity that eventually lifted hundreds of millions of Chinese people out of poverty.
Many people consider Lee Kuan Yew, the founder and long-serving prime minister of Singapore, to be a great leader, although he may have wished to showcase his talents on a larger stage.
In fact, the size of a country does not seem to affect whether a person can become a great leader.
I had no intention of being disrespectful when I said that a small country like Luxembourg is unlikely to produce a great leader, especially since the country's political atmosphere is generally not very contentious.
The United States is vast enough to be a cradle for great leaders.
Some presidents have indeed achieved a great deal.
Harry S. Truman and Dwight D. Eisenhower — although not intellectual giants — demonstrated remarkable judgment in establishing the post-war international order that supported world peace for decades.
Others, including Ronald Reagan and Bill Clinton, possessed high talent — namely, the ability to inspire and the art of persuasion.
John F. Kennedy was fortunate to have both.
He accomplished a great task: resolving the Cuban Missile Crisis.
His gift for inspiration was unparalleled; in fact, his assassination after his death consolidated the tradition he left behind.
In South Africa, no one has yet been considered a great figure since the death of President Mandela, who combined courage, authority, and graceful magnanimity.
In fact, he was the most charming leader I have ever seen; the other two — former UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan and former US Secretary of State Colin Powell — are either Africans or African Americans.
What about today?
The only one qualified to claim greatness is the de facto leader of the European Union, German Chancellor Angela Merkel.
Like former Chancellor Helmut Kohl, she was often underestimated at the beginning but rarely made mistakes when making important decisions.
Kohl formulated generous terms for German unification; Merkel opposed Putin when he invaded Ukraine and adopted a tolerant attitude toward the refugee crisis.
I think Marx and Tolstoy are wrong.
Political leaders —— those who exercise political power —— can change the situation, whether for better or worse.
Merkel is today's most obvious example, as she has pointed the way for Europe to deal with a high-difficulty survival crisis.
